stimulus:
["
Please note that this experiment is only designed to work from a computer or laptop. Please do not continue if you are using a phone, tablet, or other mobile device. If you are on a phone, tablet or other mobile device you will need to return to Prolific and click \"stop without completing\".

If you are currently seeing this page from a laptop or computer, please click on the \"Continue\" button.
"]

We wanted to provide a heads-up that the end of the experiment will consist of an anonymous survey with multiple questions. A few questions are open-ended questions where you need to type 1-2 sentences. Sometimes participants do not like answering open-ended questions and tend to quit a survey once they see such questions.

If a sizable number of people quit a survey halfway, the responses will no longer be useful. Our research depends on good quality responses. Thus, please make sure you do not mind open-ended questions before continuing with experiment.

Press 'y' on your keyboard if you agree to answer the open-ended questions at the end of the experiment.

Hello! Thank you for volunteering to help out with our study. Please take a moment to adjust your seating so that you can comfortably watch the monitor and use the keyboard. Feel free to dim the lights as well.

Close the door or do whatever is necessary to minimize disturbance during the experiment. Please also take a moment to silence your phone so that you are not interrupted by any messages mid-experiment. Do not switch to any other tabs or windows until you are complete.

We will now go over the instructions. Please read these carefully, as you will not be able to complete this experiment without following them precisely.

A "Next" button will appear at the bottom of the screen on each page. This button will be greyed out at the beginning and will be activated after a few seconds (giving you time to read the instructions on each page). Please read everything on each page carefully before clicking on the "Next" button to continue to the next page.

In the examples so far, the rectangle alternated only one feature at a time (either its color or its size) rhythmically. In the actual experiment, both the color and the size will alternate together.

Let's see an example of this on the next page.

At the beginning of each display, you will be told which feature (color or size) to pay attention to. That is the feature you must keep track of (that feature's rhytmic changes). Whenever the instructed feature changes, you should respond by pressing the Space key. You must try to ignore the other feature, even though it may also be changing at the same time.

If you are instructed to pay attention to the color, you should press the Space key every time the rectangle changes to purple, and you should try to ignore any size changes throughout the whole display. If you are instructed to pay attention to the size, you should press the Space key every time the rectangle grows larger, and you should try to ignore color changes.

Because the alternations can be quite fast, you should try to press the Space key as quickly as possible when the relevant change occurs.

Let's practice first with the color feature.

Pay attention to the Color change (press the Space key everytime the rectangle turns purple as soon as possible) and ignore the Size change.

Click on the 'Start' button to start the display. Since the display will start immediately,you should be ready to press the 'Space' key as soon as the rectangle starts alternating its color.

Pay attention to the Size change (press the Space key everytime the rectangle grows larger as soon as possible) and ignore the Color change.

Click on the 'Start' button to start the display.

That's it. You will just do this same task for about 10 minutes. The rhythm of alternation will vary from one display to the next. Sometimes the color alternation will be faster than the size alternation, sometimes the size will be faster than the color.

Regardless of these variations, your task remains the same. If you are asked to pay attention to the color, press the Space key everytime the rectangle changes to purple as soon as possible and ignore the size changes. If you are asked to pay attention to the size, press the Space key everytime the rectangle grows larger as soon as possible and ignore the color changes.

You may find it difficult at times to ignore the other feature, and that is completely normal. The experiment is designed to be challenging in this way. Please do your best to stay focused for the whole task, as your responses are only useful if you give your full attention to the instructed feature.

Please always use your dominant hand to press the 'Space' key. You can now start the experiment when you are ready.

response: {"age":"29","gender":"male","testing":"I think that this experiment may have been testing our ability to isolate stimuli in a \"noisy\" visual environment, along with our tendency to anticipate changes based on certain visual patterns. I suspect that the \"distraction\" created by the change that we were supposed to ignore (i.e., the color change when we were tracking the size change, or the size change when we were tracking the color change) may mislead some participants into tapping the space bar at a rhythm that is inconsistent with the specific characteristic that we were supposed to be monitoring.","attention":"100","strategy":"I did not use any particular, well-defined strategy when doing the experiment, but I did find myself consciously resisting the urge to tap the space bar in a predictable rhythm; to avoid falling \"out of tune\" with the changes unfolding on my screen, I tried to wait until the size or color of the shape had changed (depending on which change I was supposed to be responding to in any given session of the experiment) before tapping the space bar. On a couple of occasions, I caught myself reflexively tapping the space bar before the anticipated change had actually occurred onscreen.","other":"No, I do not have any other observations to report. Thank you for allowing me to participate in your research!","errors":"No, there were no parts of the experiment in which the text was cut off or misaligned. Everything was displayed appropriately."}
